First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B, which is denoted as A ∆ B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

A ∆ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

A ∪ B = {5, 7, 9, 13, 15, 20}
A ∩ B = {9, 13}

A ∆ B = {5, 7, 15, 20}

Now, let's find (A ∆ B) ∪ A and (A ∪ A) ∆ (B ∪ B):

(A ∆ B) ∪ A = {5, 7, 9, 13, 15, 20} (since A is already included in A ∪ B)

(A ∪ A) ∆ (B ∪ B) = A ∆ B (since A ∪ A = A and B ∪ B = B)

A ∆ B = {5, 7, 15, 20}

Now, we can see that (A ∆ B) ∪ A = (A ∪ A) ∆ (B ∪ B), which is {5, 7, 9, 13, 15, 20}. This shows that the symmetric difference of two sets is distributive over union.
